---
import TypographyDemoLayout from '../layouts/TypographyDemoLayout.astro';

const codeSnippet = `export const getStaticPaths = async ({ paginate }) => {
  const posts = await getCollection('blog');
  return paginate(posts, { pageSize: 10 });
};`;
---

<TypographyDemoLayout title="Typography demo — Poppins, IBM Plex Mono, Fraunces">
  <p class="type-label">Typography demo</p>
  <h1 class="type-hero">Brutalist editorial from the future</h1>
  <p class="type-meta">Poppins · IBM Plex Mono · Fraunces</p>

  <p class="type-body">
    This page shows how the three fonts work together: <strong>Poppins</strong> for structure and reading,
    <strong>IBM Plex Mono</strong> for system and data, and <strong>Fraunces</strong> for editorial accent.
    Human readability comes first; type does the work.
  </p>

  <h2 class="type-heading-2">Headings in Poppins</h2>
  <p class="type-body">
    Headings use Poppins at 600–700 weight with tight letter-spacing. Body copy stays at 400 (or 500 for lead paragraphs)
    with a relaxed line-height so long reads stay comfortable. This is what a typical article opener might look like.
  </p>

  <h2 class="type-heading-2">Mono for system and code</h2>
  <p class="type-meta">2025-03-02 · 4 min read</p>
  <p class="type-body">
    Dates, tags, and labels use IBM Plex Mono in small sizes with uppercase and letter-spacing. Inline code
    like <code class="type-code-inline">getStaticPaths()</code> or <code class="type-code-inline">paginate()</code>
    stays in mono so it reads as technical without breaking the flow.
  </p>
  <pre class="type-code-block"><code>{codeSnippet}</code></pre>

  <h2 class="type-heading-2">Fraunces for editorial accent</h2>
  <p class="type-body">
    The serif is used sparingly: pull quotes, bylines, or a single line that should feel authored rather than systematic.
  </p>
  <blockquote class="type-pullquote type-pullquote--italic">
    Use Fraunces for one or two sentences that need to breathe. Less is more—keep it special.
  </blockquote>
  <p class="type-byline">By the design system</p>
  <p class="type-body">
    Bylines can sit in Fraunces for a soft editorial touch, or in mono for a more utilitarian feel. Tags below
    stay in mono so the hierarchy stays clear.
  </p>
  <p class="type-tags">system-design · human-agent · typography · editorial</p>

  <h2 class="type-heading-2">Full specimen summary</h2>
  <ul class="type-body" style="list-style: disc; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
    <li><strong>Poppins</strong>: headings (600–700), body (400–500), nav and UI</li>
    <li><strong>IBM Plex Mono</strong>: code, dates, tags, captions, labels</li>
    <li><strong>Fraunces</strong>: pull quotes, bylines, section intros</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="type-body">
    Review this demo at <code class="type-code-inline">/typography-demo</code>. When you’re happy with the pairing,
    we can apply the same stack to the blog.
  </p>
</TypographyDemoLayout>
